    ,('Knight Foundation','National Center for Civic Innovation',74900.0,NULL,NULL,'donation log','Communities','https://knightfoundation.org/grants/6129',NULL,'Grant period: 09/01/2013 - 08/31/2014; goal: For The GovLab @NYU to conduct a census of existing companies using open data to be able to provide insight and recommendations that will lead to a better understanding of opportunities for companies to invest in open data.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'The GovLab @ NYU')
    ,('Knight Foundation','Benwood Foundation',50000.0,NULL,NULL,'donation log','Communities','https://knightfoundation.org/grants/6023',NULL,'Grant period: 09/01/2013 - 09/01/2014; goal: Building on successful efforts to make city data more accessible, the Chattanooga Open Government Collaborative will use challenge funding to train key groups in using the available information. Building on successful efforts to make city data more accessible, the Chattanooga Open Government Collaborative will use challenge funding to train key groups, including journalists and city employees, in using the available information. The Chattanooga Public Library will create an online portal housing community data, and provide workshops and training on how best to use it to better the community. To start, the collaborative will focus on six community groups interested in a specific issue like public safety. At the end of one year, the collaborative hopes to have an engaged community of data consumers helping to identify needs and assist in designing and utilizing open data tools.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Chattanooga Open Government Collaborative')
    ,('Knight Foundation','The Boston Foundation',50000.0,NULL,NULL,'donation log','Communities','https://knightfoundation.org/grants/6025',NULL,'Grant period: 09/01/2013 - 09/01/2014; goal: This partnership will launch a statewide education reporting project creating space for thoughtful conversation around improving Massachusetts schools. This partnership—between the Boston Foundation, public radio station WBUR and Glass Eye Media—will launch a statewide education reporting project creating space for thoughtful conversation around improving Massachusetts schools. The project will use Glass Eye Media’s structured beat approach used in its site Homicide Watch, WBUR’s editorial resources and the Boston Foundation’s connection to the education community to build data, tools and change. The project will increase the station’s capacity to cover education, and build a replicable framework for effective coverage of education reform in other regions and states.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Improving Education Coverage in Mass.')
